<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is strike water temperature?", answer: "Strike water is the hot water poured over crushed grain to start the mash in all-grain brewing. The strike water needs to be hotter than the desired mash temperature because the cool, dry grain absorbs heat from the water. The strike temperature is the precise temperature that, after mixing with the grain, will land at your target mash temperature." },
  { question: "What formula does this calculator use?", answer: "It uses John Palmer's standard infusion equation: Strike Temp equals 0.2 divided by the water-to-grain ratio in quarts per pound, multiplied by the difference between target mash temp and grain temp, plus the target mash temp. The 0.2 constant is the ratio of the specific heat of grain to water." },
  { question: "What is a typical water-to-grain ratio?", answer: "Most homebrewers use 1.25 to 1.5 quarts of water per pound of grain, which is roughly 2.6 to 3.1 liters per kilogram. Lower ratios produce a stiffer, more concentrated mash often used for German lagers. Higher ratios produce a thinner, looser mash that is easier to stir and lauter and more common in American ale brewing." },
  { question: "Why does my strike water need to be hotter than the mash temp?", answer: "The crushed grain enters the mash at room temperature, around 65 to 75 degrees Fahrenheit, and absorbs heat from the strike water. Grain has roughly one fifth the heat capacity of water by weight, but the temperature drop on contact is still significant. For a typical 10 pound grain bill at 1.25 quarts per pound striking 152 degrees, you need about 165 degree water." },
  { question: "Can I trust the calculator exactly?", answer: "The formula is accurate to within about 1 to 2 degrees Fahrenheit if your inputs are correct. The two biggest sources of error are inaccurate grain temperature and the heat absorbed by the mash tun itself. Pre-heating your mash tun with hot water and discarding it before adding strike water removes most of the tun absorption, and reading grain temperature with a probe before mashing in eliminates the rest of the guesswork." }
]) %>

